12/05/2009
NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop Scheffer was in Skopje on Friday (May 8th) for a farewell visit before he steps down from his post this summer. De Hoop Scheffer met with Macedonian President Branko Crvenkovski, Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski and President-elect Gjorge Ivanov. Discussions focused on resolving the name dispute with Greece and Macedonia's NATO bid. Former Danish Prime Minister Anders Fogh Rasmussen succeeds de Hoop Scheffer on August 1st. 
*** 
Greek Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis said on Monday (May 11th) that his country remains in favour of Turkey's EU accession prospects, as long as Ankara "completely and effectively" fulfils Union requirements. Karamanlis make these comments after talks with his Swedish counterpart Fredrik Reinfeldt during an official visit to Stockholm. Reinfeldt, whose country will take over the EU rotating presidency next July, urged the EU to fulfil its commitments towards Turkey. The two prime ministers also discussed international measures to tackle the global economic crisis and climate change, as well as developments on the Balkans, the Cyprus question and the issue of illegal immigration. 
*** 
Serbia and Macedonia on Thursday (May 7th) agreed to focus on deepening co-operation and bridge their differences regarding the Kosovo issue. "We should concentrate on what brings us close and not on what separates us," Serbian Foreign Minister Vuk Jeremic said after meeting Macedonian counterpart Antonio Milososki in Skopje. Milososki stressed that mutual goals are much bigger than differences. 
*** 
Romanian Foreign Minister Cristian Diaconescu was in the United States last week, where he met with Vice President Joseph Biden and Secretary of State Hillary Clinton. They discussed prospects for abolishing US visas for Romanian citizens and bilateral co-operation on security, economic and regional issues. There are positive indications the visa regime between Romania and the United States may disappear by the end of the year, Diaconescu said before heading to Washington. 
*** 
Kosovo President Fatmir Sejdiu said on Sunday (May 10th) he had not received an invitation from Macedonia's state authorities to attend Tuesday's inauguration of new President Gjorge Ivanov in Skopje. Media reports suggested Skopje is reluctant to risk offending representatives of Serbia who are expected to attend the ceremony. 
*** 
Serbian President Boris Tadic and Prime Minister Mirko Cvetkovic met with High Representative in Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) Valentin Inzko in Belgrade on May 5th. They voiced full support for the integrity and territorial sovereignty of BiH. Inzko also met with Serbian Deputy Prime Minister Bozidar Djelic to discuss the European integration of the Balkans and regional economic co-operation. 
(Various sources -- 05/05/09-12/05/09) 
